      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Khornette wrote:</div><div class="orig"> <br />First of all, didn't that just prove that the more SP proc was the damage and not the debuff? Secondly, you can't even be sure which part of the 2 SP gain was for debuff and for damage hit, how do you prove that? Damage hit -&gt; SP also get SP bonus from the party size too, unless your normal attack on the Thickshell gives 1 SP, then that 30 SP gain maybe reasonably the damage did by Trammel. As far as I can recall, crap normal attack on Thickshell give somewhere from 20-30 SP as well unless that Thickshell is actually GREEN to you ALONE. Finally, SP gains are still random to some extent, there is actually no proof against or for any theory right now.</div></div> <br /> <br />You can tell whether the SP comes from the damage or the debuff by looking at in which order they appear in the combat log. SP gains between the damage line and the debuff line come from damage and the debuff gain comes after the debuff line. This is easy to test by simply soloing using Heavy Thrust a lot as you'll notice the pattern very quickly. Numbers appearing right after the damage line consistently give large gains while those appearing below the debuff line struggle to break 20. In a crab party this pattern is reversed. <br /> <br />In most situations you can deal enough damage to easily surpass the tiny debuff gain with damage procs, however, when you deal &lt;20 damage per hit in a large party you'll notice your damage SP is crippled so hard even the party bonus won't save it while the debuff procs multiply far above solo numbers. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov  8th 2010  8:10am by Omena </span></i></div>
